ce:section.ce:para:
To investigate the TC recognition mechanism, UV absorption, fluorescence, zeta potential, and fluorescence lifetime are examined for CDs, CDs-Eu3+, and CDs-Eu3+-TC (Fig. 3
                        ). TC exhibit a maximum UV absorption at 356 nm and do not emit fluorescence at 390 nm, as shown in Fig. 3A and B. CDs emit fluorescence at 545 nm at 390 nm. However, adding Eu3+ results in a decreases fluorescence intensity of CDs at 545 nm. The zeta potential of CDs is −17.4 mV (Fig. 3C), which increases to +13.7 mV after cationic Eu3+ addition, suggesting that positively charged Eu3+ ions bind to the CDs' surface to form the ground state complex CDs-Eu3+. CDs, Eu3+ and CDs-Eu3+ have little UV absorption at 340 nm⁓450 nm. Adding TC to CDs-Eu3+ redshifts the UV absorption wavelength from 356 to 395 nm. The zeta potential further decreases to +3.7 mV, indicating the formation of the CDs-Eu3+-TC complex. Since the energy absorbed by TC is efficiently transferred to Eu3+ via an “antenna effect”, CDs-Eu3+-TC shows red fluorescence at 619 nm [33,34]. Moreover, the CDs’ excitation spectra mostly overlap the Eu3+-TC absorption spectrum (Fig. 3A and Fig. S2). Thus, the TC-induced fluorescence quenching of CDs at 545 nm is attributed to the internal filtering effect (IFE). From Table S1, it could be seen that the correlation coefficients (R

                           2
                        ) of the bi-exponential model and tri-exponential model are the same. Therefore, the bi-exponential model was chosen to fit the fluorescence lifetimes of CDs, CDs-Eu3+ and CDs-Eu3+-TC [35,36]. The fluorescence lifetimes of CD, CDs-Eu3+ and CDs-Eu3+-TC are 4.697, 3.129, and 2.452 ns, respectively (Fig. 3D and Table S2).

Under optimal conditions, the sensitivity of the established ratiometric fluorescence system is evaluated for TC (Fig. 5AB). With the increase in TC concentration, the fluorescence intensity at 545 nm gradually decreases, while the fluorescence intensity at 619 nm increases. Accordingly, the solution's fluorescence color changes from yellow to red. The results reflect that the response value of the fluorescent probes (I619/I545) is linearly correlated with the TC concentration (1⁓100 μM), with the linear equation of I619/I545 = 0.029c+0.6209 and a correlation coefficient (R

                           2
                        ) of 0.9958. The limit of detection (LOD) of the method was calculated according to the formula LOD = 3σ/S (σ: standard deviation; S: slope). This allows further accurate quantification of TC, and the method's detection limit is 31 nM. In addition, the performance of the proposed CDs-Eu3+ method was compared with other prepared methods for detecting TC as listed in Table S3 [39–47]. Accordingly, the proposed CDs-Eu3+ method exhibited distinct advantages in terms of linear range (1⁓100 μM) and detection limits (31 nM).
